<body>
  <header>
    <h1>Understanding Linear Equations</h1>
    <p>Your guide to mastering linear functions</p>
  </header>

  <section>
    <h2>What is a Linear Equation?</h2>
    <p>A linear equation is an equation between two variables that gives a straight line when plotted on a graph. It has the form:</p>
    <p><strong>y = mx + b</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>m</strong> is the slope (rate of change)</li>
      <li><strong>b</strong> is the y-intercept (where the line crosses the y-axis)</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Graphing Linear Equations</h2>
    <p>To graph a linear equation, follow these steps:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Find the y-intercept (b) and plot it on the y-axis.</li>
      <li>Use the slope (m) to determine the next point.</li>
      <li>Draw a straight line through the points.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Practice Problem</h2>
    <p>Graph the equation: <strong>y = 2x + 1</strong></p>
    <p>Solution:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>y-intercept = 1 → Plot (0,1)</li>
      <li>Slope = 2 → Rise 2, run 1 → Next point: (1,3)</li>
      <li>Draw a line through (0,1) and (1,3)</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

